<span id="freeTextContainer16853398017288578385"><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1501006436i/23407588._SX540_.png' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/><b><u>Book 2</u> : <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2071620939' rel='nofollow noopener'>Fractured</a></b> ★★★1/2<br/><b><u>Book 3</u> : <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2072732512' rel='nofollow noopener'>Genesis/Undone</a></b> ★<br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1501014957i/23408747._SX540_.png' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>I&apos;ve said it before, but the <i>whodunits</i> and what not aren&apos;t what compel me to read thrillers, but rather <b>the unflinching look they take at the most gruesome and disgusting parts of our human world.</b> I&apos;ve guessed who the killer was in <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/21681.Darkness__Take_My_Hand__Kenzie___Gennaro___2_' title='Darkness, Take My Hand (Kenzie &amp; Gennaro, #2) by Dennis Lehane' rel='nofollow noopener'>Darkness, Take My Hand</a> halfway through it, and it remains one of my favorite thriller, because sometimes, the characterization, the <i>Hows</i> and <i>Whens</i> and <i>Whys</i> are just so much more important and interesting than the big r</span>
  <span id="freeText16853398017288578385" style="display:none"><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1501006436i/23407588._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><b><u>Book 2</u> : <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2071620939" rel="nofollow noopener">Fractured</a></b> ★★★1/2<br><b><u>Book 3</u> : <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2072732512" rel="nofollow noopener">Genesis/Undone</a></b> ★<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1501014957i/23408747._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I've said it before, but the <i>whodunits</i> and what not aren't what compel me to read thrillers, but rather <b>the unflinching look they take at the most gruesome and disgusting parts of our human world.</b> I've guessed who the killer was in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/21681.Darkness__Take_My_Hand__Kenzie___Gennaro___2_" title="Darkness, Take My Hand (Kenzie &amp; Gennaro, #2) by Dennis Lehane" rel="nofollow noopener">Darkness, Take My Hand</a> halfway through it, and it remains one of my favorite thriller, because sometimes, the characterization, the <i>Hows</i> and <i>Whens</i> and <i>Whys</i> are just so much more important and interesting than the big reveal. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1501014957i/23408748._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><b><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/21717.Triptych__Will_Trent___1_" title="Triptych (Will Trent, #1) by Karin Slaughter" rel="nofollow noopener">Triptych</a> is one of these books.</b> Even though I've known - <i>known</i> - in my core who the psychopath was for more than 200 pages, I couldn't look away until the very end. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/12504.Karin_Slaughter" title="Karin Slaughter" rel="nofollow noopener">Karin Slaughter</a> puts so much care in her characters - villains included - that even though you want them to burn, you don't want them to get caught in some two-pages scene and call it a day : you want closure, and she delivers. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1501014957i/23408749._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I'm going to warn you : <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/21717.Triptych__Will_Trent___1_" title="Triptych (Will Trent, #1) by Karin Slaughter" rel="nofollow noopener">Triptych</a> is short on likeable characters, and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/12504.Karin_Slaughter" title="Karin Slaughter" rel="nofollow noopener">Karin Slaughter</a> doesn't shy away from picturing <b>gruesome violence on page,</b> so perhaps don't read it if that's something that could trigger you. The story being told through multiple - and unreliable - narrators, I can assure you that you'll want OUT of several of these minds. I've been feeling on the edge of vomiting from page one, and Will's chapters were the only ones that could bring a tiny smile on my face. Will, whose name prevented me from stopping my read when I realized - thanks to the series' name and friends' reviews - that <i>he</i> was meant to be the hero, and not that fucker of Michael Ormewood. Will, whom I wanted to protect from the moment I met him, probably because of his dyslexia and the way people - and himself - treated him. As a teacher, I've seen too often how self-depreciation can go hands in hands with learning disorders, and it breaks my heart every damned time. Oh, and probably because he's the only character who's thoroughly likeable and did I say that you'll want to protect him? Yeah? <br><br>In the end, I feel sick to my stomach but I can't deny that I don't regret starting this series for one second : thrillers whose appeal doesn't revolve around some final twist are way too rare for me to look away, and I'll definitely read more of Will Trent's investigations really soon. <b>Recommended.</b><br><br><b>TW - <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[rape, attempted rape, pedophilia, graphic violence, ableist, homophobic, sexist and racist slurs <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></b><br><br><i>For more of my reviews, please visit:</i><br><blockquote>
  <a href="https://meetthebookworld.com/" rel="nofollow noopener">
